snippet.textDisplay:
I like the characters of Zach and Clay, Zach mostly because he is the only one who showed any kind of character development going from some kinda douche to actually being genuinely concerned, he's believable in his motives and seems to just been peer pressured into doing all that crap in season 1 which he thought were just "innocent jokes" or something like that at the time.


Clay mostly because he seems like a believable character, though he is way too trusting to everyone he meets; I have known people like that, people that probably would justify to try and set a possible school shooter straight, so he doesnt seem too far fetched for me, but I don't get how he didn't see through all the bullshit. Killing someone is never justified, why the fuck would they cover it up? For Clay I get it, he seems to act as a sort-of white knight dude believing in the good of every person. He clearly is the furthest off of being "responsible" for Hannahs suicide, that I still don't get btw, since she chose to do so many idiotic things... Alex has to be a deeply deranged individual. He tried to kill himself, and then he actually killed another person and framed someone just because they thought it was "morally grey justice", lol.


And the people actually justifying Bryce's or even Monty's actions, like that gay love interest of Monty, or Ani for Bryce? Dude. That is just showing how idiotic those characters must be. I mean, what the fuck?


Season One was decent, Season Two was like stepping down about half of a staircase, and Season Three just crashed into the floor to the basement at the bottom of the staircase...

snippet.textDisplay:
"Élite" achieves what this season of 13RW couldn't (*spoilers ahead*):
In season 1's finale, we discover that Polo murdered Marina.
Season 2's arch is all about him being exposed for what he did, and getting away with it at the end.
Finally, in season 3 he's murdered after FINALLY redeeming himself: he's going to confess and convinced his parents to not cancell Lu and Nadia's scholarship.

Why does Polo's character arch work? Because he's a round character: he regrets what he did, as it was an accident. We know his backstory, and can relate to him in some way. He's the antagonist, but his personality isn't solely based in him being a psychopath or an extremely evil person. He's a regular teen, who happened to kill someone by accident and was very afraid of the consequences of his actions. He let everyone decide for him (Carla, his parents, Cayetana...), and it wasn't until he decided to start living his own life that he had the courage to confess.

"Élite" it's still a teen drama like 13RW, but I think no one can argue how great some of its characters are.
